\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Scarcity - A term used by Fred Hirsch in a theory to explain distribution
 of resources in a society.
 Scarcity is the perceived or real lack of products or services created
 by a competition for them which is intensified by population growth ( through
 increased productivity and time costs).
 Scarcities can be either direct or indirect and thus - physical or social.
 Hirsch also points out that social scarcities are becoming physical scarcities
 (so this distinction isn't so clear after all).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Congestion - The competition for resources in the context of modern Western
 society where physical scarcities (severe shortages of food and shelter)
 have been largely conquered.
 In Hirsch's theory, congestion is a side-effect of commercialization and
 removal of older social barriers.
 Since all goods and amenities are available through money, the competition
 and scarcity for what used to be accessible to only the top few have intensifie
d.
 With economic progress therefore, consumers are more - not less - driven
 by status needs than before.
 Writing in what is now called the affluent 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gilded age
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the United States, Veblen had discussed the same phenomenon that had
 revived the need for status signaling.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Status
\series bold
 Competitions 
\series default
- A term used by Robert H.
 Frank (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"

\end_inset

) to denote the basic needs amongst individuals to feel important relative
 to others.
 Status competitions therefore operate at a lower granularity than social
 congestion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Signaling - The mechanism that consumers use to indicate status in society
 - a concept strongly tied to the idea of indicating status through purchasing
 of items available in the market (therefore the term is used a lot in the
 various models for conspicuous consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility,ireland_signals"

\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Positional 
\series bold
goods - 
\series default
Goods that are used to indicate status as opposed to goods that serve individual
 needs or welfare.
 The distinction between positional and non-positional goods is often dependent
 on the welfare function.
 Also known as status-indicating goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Snob 
\series bold
and Bandwagon items 
\series default
- Snob items are items whose demand declines as they become more popular
 i.e.
 are consumed by more people - whereas Bandwagon items are those whose demand
 increase as more people consume them.
 These terms are used in a model for conspicuous consumption provided by
 Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 - where consumers derive their utility from how other perceive or view
 the user's consumption.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
\paragraph_spacing single
Visible 
\series bold
Consumption 
\series default
- The consumption of items that are used to indicate status.
 Visible consumption encompasses the purchase of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

signaling
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 items i.e.
 items that others can view to infer status of the individual.
 This definition of conspicuous consumption is particularly tractable to
 mathematical modeling as measurable status inferences can readily become
