\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Status-as-lagged-consumption"

\end_inset

Status as lagged asset ownership and consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How societies perceive differences in status amongst themselves is difficult
 to record - let alone standardize it across multiple geographies.
 Relying on the consumption microdata, we only record the assets and income
 of individuals that the higher-status individuals are more likely to acquire
 than the low status individuals.
 Our view of status comprises strictly of i) possessions (assets and consumption
) and ii) the barriers to possessions.
 These status determinants enhance status by more consumption or more assets
 - in the sense that consumption and assets add to existing possessions.
 An individual is imparted a higher status when more barriers exist for
 others to acquire the possessions than those that exist for herself.
 It is even possible that possessions translate as status only through barriers
 (items that have no other value except through barriers that exist to acquire
 them).
 The role of conspicuous consumption then is to distort the status derived
 from other determinants of status.
 Through consumption, status items may be used to to overcome the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

barriers
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to status (thus changing them).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Buying an item that was previously limited to someone with a higher status
 than oneself invariably enhances one's status.
 Inherited or acquired assets also have the similar effect of enhancing
 one's status.
 However, the consumption on expendable items being more affordable than
 acquisition of long-term assets may imply prevalence of the former in societies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a model for status, the barriers can be quantified in terms of i) the
 weights of that personal characteristics of an individual carry (parameters
 such as locality, age, gender, ethnicity) or ii) the prices for assets
 or non-durable items in the market.
 More consumption on items that may changes one's perceived status may imply
 more perceived inequalities in the society.
 The model provided by Coreno et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

 is instructive in this regard.
 The model (
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

) considers a ranking function for every individual where consumption is
 seen as a way to transform the income ranking of a population i.e.
 individuals improve their perception in society through consumption (and/or
 asset ownership) to overcome their income rank in the society.
 It can be asserted that anyone in less than the highest income group (more
 specifically -the highest quantile of the all status determinants minus
 that of consumption) would benefit from a short-term expense on status-related
 consumption.
 Therefore, one can claim that the consumption rank (or utility) and non-consump
tion status rank (or utility) must differ for the consumers in medium quantiles
 - if conspicuous consumption exists in a society.
 This verification my serve as the test of conspicuous consumption (a similar
 inference may be drawn from the permanent income elasticity of conspicuous
 consumption within different quantiles of a population).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discussion on barriers is incomplete without a clear definition of status
 - a ranking of consumption and asset ownership requires a specification
 of how expenditure or budget share is combined for the consumers.
 Unlike many other models for conspicuous consumption, we assume that all
 consumption items can impart status.
 We identify three factors that contribute to status through consumption
 (these are detailed in subsequent sections).
 Instead of agreeing on a crisp boundary between conspicuous and non-conspicuous
 items, we attempt to develop a criterion to sort the items in terms of
 their status impact (i.e.
 the status utility that a consumer may derive).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A claim that we intend to test is whether the consumption on items that
 have a high impact on status must decrease (increase) with the decrease
 (increase) in gaps in assets and other barriers in the society over time.
 In other words, more significant differences in determinants of status
 must correspond to an increase in consumption of the consumers for those
 with a medium rank of status.
 A quantile regression on a time-series can test whether the purchases of
 status items is different across income quantiles of the society over time.
\end_layout

