 In Tanzania, for example, the investments from South Africa and Western
 countries have expanded significantly.
 Not all countries in the region have seen a similar scale of investments.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We only consider district level residence and primary spoken language as
 the demographic factors that may affect status consumption.
 Amongst all the factors that one may find relevant for status in a society,
 we find wealth, ownership of assets and the degree of crowding towards
 new items (loosely determining the barriers to status) of key importance
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The personal characteristics (such as region, socio-economic class) may
 be relevant for stats only through ownership of assets in the long-run.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Wealth and Assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The accumulated wealth being a universal indicator of status, the distribution
 of income and assets is the most likely to influence the consumption of
 items that affect status.
 We consider ownership of assets and the barriers which may exist to acquiring
 them as the only long term determinant of status in a society.
 What we consider as asset in the economy is any item that is owned on a
 permanent basis (rented or borrowed items are not considered assets, but
 gifted or inherited items are).
 The notion of wealth or permanent income is also seen as an asset in this
 view.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Supply
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Status is a complex sociological phenomenon.
 While the buyer of an item indicates her status to the immediate local
 surroundings through her consumption, the items she ends up buying depend
 on more than just her preferences - since there can be wide disparities
 in the environments where consumers in a population reside.
 If the items available to the consumers in different regions within an
 economy are disparate, then it is no longer to trivial to identify items
 relevant for status and infer demographic unevenness in the purchase of
 status items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's take example of the availability of electricity in Tanzania.
 If only the rich could afford electricity, then it being used by a smaller
 and richer part of the population may seem to have less significance than
 weddings - which are ubiquitous in the population (a regression with quantities
 consumed as dependent variable would bear more significance for items consumed
 by more consumers).
 One may be tempted to argue that items consumed by more people carry more
 significance for status than the item that is hardly accessible to the
 wider population, but status in a society is driven by both the supply
 of the item and the ability of the individual to purchase the item (disposable
 income).
 The interplay of supply, wealth and assets determine status in a society.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
\begin_inset VSpace medskip*
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\paragraph_spacing single
Overcrowding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While supply and wealth influence the long-term development of status, one
 cannot ignore how introduction of new industrial goods can create demand
 and distort the distribution of resources (through industrial development,
 migrations etc.).
 With the introduction of a new status item e.g.
 a new electronic product, there is a tendency amongst the consumers to
 flock towards the item.
 The demand for certain status items is enhanced by the popularity of the
 item itself.
 Enhanced by the advertising effects, such items often create a market of
 their own.
 This so-called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bandwagon
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 effect is essential to indicating one's social standing (see Corneo et
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"

\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\paragraph_spacing single
Empirically, the change of the budget share (or elasticities) of the item
 over a time-period with respect to lagged consumption, income and supply
 can indicate how such a bandwagon-effect develops.
 The budget share for an item can shift when its supply is increased (more
 electrical power plants or cheaper alternative energy would reduce the
 budget share on electricity).
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Not all status goods need to exhibit flocking of consumers.
 If the item has been restricted to the richer section of the society for
 a long time, then increase in abundance of the item can actually cause
 disinterest in that item.
 These are considered the snob items in literature
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Hirsch's argument for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

overuse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 being a criterion for signaling items - i.e.
 the decline in signaling qualities of an item when the consumers use it
 too much - essentially points to the existence of snob items.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As new items can always appear in the market through innovation or imports,
 a consumer uses both snob and bandwagon items to indicate her status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The demand for industrial goods is particularly relevant in the sub-Saharan
 African context.
 As discussed in previous sections, the outreach and resources of the government
al institutions in African countries are limited and a large industrial
 sector at the scale of China has been out of reach for most African countries
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BardhanGiants"

\end_inset

.
 The small-scale private enterprise - which forms the majority of non-agrarian
 workforce in sub-Saharan Africa - receives very little governmental assistance
 and hence the expansion of informal economy has continued with the migration
 to urban areas increasing significantly over the last decades.
 The interaction between urban and rural regions is of significance to any
 study of consumption in the sub-Saharan Africa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Often viewed as a necessary phase of development, urban migration leads
 to the competition between industrial and agricultural sectors for labour
 and food ( see Lewis
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GollinLRF"

\end_inset

 model - which expects the prices of food to rise as labour moves from agricultu
re to industry).
 In our view, the flight to urban areas is not merely an escape from despondent
 circumstances but the also the access to expanded consumption basket and
 a chance for improbable social mobilities.
 The introduction of industrial goods and the status needs of the consumers
 is therefore relevant to the trend of urban migration in sub-Saharan Africa
