status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In absence of observed prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}$
\end_inset

, one can instead estimate prices as 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{A}/q_{A}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{B}/q_{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Relying on total quantity (
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

) consumed of an item or the expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $(e=q\cdot p)$
\end_inset

 on the item does not serve as metric of status carrying potential as it
 can obfuscate the sense of status consumption.
 If for example, a consumer accumulates cheaper varieties of the an item
 instead of accumulating the higher priced varieties of the item, the comparison
 of quantities would no longer provide an accurate representation of the
 status-related consumption.
 If the prices of an item are 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}(where\ p_{1}>p_{2})$
\end_inset

 - which can be consumed by 
\begin_inset Formula $A,B$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}\cdot q_{A}<p_{2}\cdot q_{B}$
\end_inset

 s(or 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{A}<e_{B})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{A}<q_{B}$
\end_inset

, consumer B accumulates cheaper varieties of the item.
 If we don't observe 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1},p_{2}$
\end_inset

 directly but observe the total consumption on the item by 
\begin_inset Formula $A(=e_{A})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, then even 
