A preliminary analysis of budget ratios
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\bar under
There is always a temptation to think of an average total expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 so that an expensive product (and therefore a status product) is simply
 one with price 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}>\gamma x_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 represents a threshold proportion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\theta}$
\end_inset

.
 For example, if we want to consider any item that costs more than half
 of the total expenditure of 80% of a population, we set 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 to be the 80% quantile of the total expenditures in the population and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=0.5$
\end_inset

.
 While 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\theta}$
\end_inset

 does provide us the items that are more expensive for most people - such
 products are not necessarily status products.
 In fact, the average (or median) of quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}/x$
\end_inset

 i.e.
 the average budget ratio of all items is an equivalent measure.
 As discussed previously in the Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:precentile_threshold_method"

\end_inset

, items thus identified are not necessarily status items - but simply the
 less affordable items that we may consider as those with status carrying
 potential.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The differences between amounts spent by the lowest and higher percentile
 of spenders of a particular commodity are expected to be higher when a
 commodity is a status-good than when it is of common utility.
 The illustrations show non-zero log-level expenditure on a few commodities
 when the lower (let's say 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

) percentile of the consumption of the commodity is ignored.
 Ignoring the bottom 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 percentile of the consumption of a visible commodity is equivalent to treating
 the bottom 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 percentile expenditure as non-visible consumption (If we consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta=10\%$
\end_inset

 for electricity, then bottom 10% percentile of the consumption on electricity
 would be considered non-visible and anything above that level would be
 considered visible).
 The plots of log-expenditures are shown with rising 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 (starting with the lowest percentile 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to lowest non-zero log-level of consumption of the commodity).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
For a good that is not status-related, one expects that the consumers from
 lower and higher quantiles of total expenditure (x-axis) would consume
 similar amounts of the good (y-axis).
 For a positional good, the consumers spending higher expenditure on the
 good would lean towards consumers with higher total expenditure.
 This does not indicate signaling in any way - but tests only whether a
 commodity is consumed uniformly amongst those with lower and higher total
 expenditure outlays (this is rather a measure of scarcity of the item than
 of its visibility).
 Choosing different thresholds (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta)$
\end_inset

 provides a a control on the degree to which a certain commodity can be
 included in a supposed conspicuous consumption basket.
 Instead of asking whether marriage spending is visible or not - for example
 - the test asks if only the richer consumers can afford a significant expenditu
re on marriage (while varying the degree of visibility attached to spending
 on marriage).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
