\begin_layout Subsection
Identification of items for status consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A general regression model to understand the consumption on status items
 can be written as the following:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
s & =\beta_{1}\phi(\sum_{i\in B}q_{i},\boldsymbol{q})+\beta_{2}z+\epsilon\label{eq:main_regression}
\end{align}

\end_inset

Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 is the relevant consumption measure for the identified consumption categories
 where status consumption is possible
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We differentiate between a category where status consumption is possible
 (through higher expenditure) from a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

status
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 category of commodities whose purchase indicates status.
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the consumption on an item 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 (
\series bold
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q}$
\end_inset


\series default
 being the vector of quantities 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{i}$
\end_inset

 ) in the basket 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a function and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 denotes the household characteristics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 can only represent consumption items whose total costs can be added up
 to the dependent variable 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 As we neither have the cost for assets owned nor the quantities of any
 non-food expenditure item, the ratio of how much a consumer buys as assets
 to how much she expends on non-durable items cannot be measured for the
 above model.
 LSMS does however record the total number of assets owned by a household.
 Thus we use an asset-ownership score as a control variable in the Equation
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 - calculated using by binary flags of different assets owned.
 For example, if we were to measure asset scores for items 
\begin_inset Formula $\{Land,TV,Iron\}$
\end_inset

, then a consumer who owns just an iron has a score 1(
\begin_inset Formula $1\times2^{0}=1$
\end_inset

), one who owns just a TV has 
\begin_inset Formula $2(0\times2^{0}+1\times2^{1})$
\end_inset

 and one who owns all the assets has the score 7 
\begin_inset Formula $(1\times2^{0}+1\times2^{1}+1\times2^{2})$
\end_inset

 .
 The asset control variable thus obtained can help determine whether asset
 ownership changes consumption on items in 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We assume separability of utility into categories energy, food, personal
 care, social functions and land-ownership - hence the Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 must be viewed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{alignat}{1}
s_{c\in\mathscr{C}} & =\beta_{1,c\in\mathscr{C}}\phi_{c}(\sum_{i\in B}q_{i},\boldsymbol{q})+\beta_{2,c\in\mathscr{C}}z+\epsilon
\end{alignat}

\end_inset

 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{C}$
\end_inset

 is the set of categories encompassing a category 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 To reiterate, we avoid viewing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

status category
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:main_regression"

\end_inset

 because of our claim that amongst available items to buy, a consumer does
 not look for a status item per se (much less so in the developing countries
 where status is derived mostly from assets owned and quality of consumption)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In fact even in the developed countries, a survey can hardly rank high-quality
 food-consumption lower or higher than ownership of a sports-watch on a
 visibility or status scale.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another simplification of the above model is through the assumption that
 visibility does not to matter at a level finer than the broad consumption
 categories of food, energy, transport, personal care, social functions
 and housing.
 Therefore, while a consumer may find food consumption less visible overall
 than energy, we don't recognise a difference in visibility between mangoes
 and spam as relevant for status utility to the consumer.
 The differences in price and in perceived quality-of-life between consuming
 these two options are what motivate the consumer - not the sense of visibility.
 These factors are measured with the price differences within the items
 in a category and the substitution between consumption and assets for similar
 needs.
 The Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:status_dimensions"

\end_inset

 details this view of status consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that education - which is acquired over long-term - is viewed as
 an asset.
 Notice also that we consider it impossible to overspend on public transport
 to substitute for not owning a car.
 Hence there is no status advantage derived by overspending on public transport
 as consumption.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 As shown in the table, visibility has no role to play other than the weight
 consumers collectively put on the widely defined categories of food, energy,
 personal care, social functions, transport and housing.
 The consumers differentiate themselves from others in their social surrounding
 by buying more newer, higher priced items as well as overspending on consumptio
n categories that help them remain in the asset ownership club (the latter
 being the justification of consumption remaining in the same functional
 category).
\end_layout

