\begin_layout Section

\size normal
Conspicuous consumption and Visibility
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Much of the literature surveyed in the study has viewed conspicuous consumption
 as visible consumption where the wastefulness of consumption by participants
 is a core concern.
 In the works of Ireland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

 and Arrow, Dasgputa 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ArrowDasgupta"

\end_inset

 and elsewhere, conspicuous consumption is seen as a difference between
 social welfare and market equilibrium.
 Of particular interest is the model of status-signaling provided by Ireland
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

 where consumers attempt to maximise a combined utility of visible (public)
 and non-visible (private) consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The utility function is modeled as 
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)f(v,w)+af(\hat{v},\hat{w})$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{v},\hat{w}$
\end_inset

 are societies' view of the consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $a(>0)$
\end_inset

 is a parameter indicating how much visible consumption matters to the consumer.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The model is of remarkable simplicity but calibrating it involves a sensitivity
-parameter of how much visible consumption matters to the consumers.
 Given the nature of status competitions in society, such a calibration
 is hardly trivial.
 A study by Heffetz
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "heffetz_visibility"

\end_inset

 using this model involved surveying a few hundreds of respondents asking
 them - quite literally - just how visible every item is for a typical consumer
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The choice of visible and non-visible goods matters more in developing markets
 where a culture of mass consumerism is only nascent and status competitions
 aren't driven by economic inequalities alone (whereas in developed markets,
 firms are quick to turn a conspicuous item into a higher-priced commodity).
 The context of exploits identified by Veblen is however still relevant
 in the developing markets
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

No class of society, not even the most abjectly poor, forgoes all customary
 conspicuous consumption
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In its original sense, conspicuous consumption is an ecological concern
 and plays within the realms of sociology
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Increased mobility of the members has also added to the facility with which
 a “social confirmation” can be attained within the class.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The research on conspicuous consumption in the developing world has often
 found that the consumption of visible items (for a certain selected criterion)
 differs significantly between social classes 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Kaus finds that black ethnic groups spend more on visible commodities than
 the white ethnic population in South Africa - arguing that status is gained
 through means other than consumption
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"

\end_inset

.
 Khamis et al find that the Muslims spend less on visible consumption items
 when compared to Hindus of same economic standing
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section

\size normal
Status differences and Conspicuous consumption
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
We find the role of perceived status differences more general and relevant
 to conspicuous consumption ins societies.
 As argued before, the role of conspicuous consumption is to signal a higher
 status.
 The need for conspicuous consumption is shaped by the owned assets as well
 as lack of availability of items (particularly in a developing country).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the relation between status differences and consumption, we
 note that the concept of status has characteristics of a feedback system
 in the long-run i.e.
 status may yield income and more assets through established social barriers
 but status itself often requires income and assets to be acquired.
 We therefore view status as a combination of the assets and the barriers
 to acquiring the assets.
 The Ireland model - popular in the literature - treats status consumption
 in a slightly different manner.
 The model views status-signaling as comprising of visible and non-visible
 goods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ireland_signals"

\end_inset

 - where the combined utility for every consumer is 
\begin_inset Formula $U=F(f(v,w),s)$
\end_inset

 - 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v,w)$
\end_inset

 being the private utility of the consumer and status 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 being an increasing function of inference of others.
 The status inference function is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $s=f(v,g(v)$
\end_inset

) where 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 denotes visual consumption and 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 - the consumption that is not directly observable.
 Every consumer optimizes the combined private and visible utility.
 A practical consideration in the model is the separation between visible
 and non-visible consumption - a boundary that requires a socio-cultural
 judgment and has been drawn using consumer surveys in the literature.
 This separation is key to additivity assumption which is at the heart of
 the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The parameter of combined utility in a simplified model - (
\begin_inset Formula $U=(1-a)\cdot f(v,w)+a\cdot f(v,g(v)$
\end_inset

) - can vary for different sections of society in the developing world.
 A view of status hierarchies is thus relevant in the developing world where
 status is often yielded through social barriers.
 We then attempt to connect these identify how these social characteristic
 may relate to conspicuous consumption in the long-run.
 For example, English literacy seems to have correlation with the consumption
 of certain scarce products in Tanzania.
 In the model of scarcity, English literacy (along with urban residence
 and other characteristics significant for consumption of scarce commodities)
 would be seen as a status good that is acquired through spending on education
 or migration (or other relevant commodities).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single

\size normal
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:caution-against-circular-definition"

\end_inset

A caution against circular interpretations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
Notice that one needs to be careful while drawing conclusions based on consumpti
on of commodities that are themselves selected based on the percentiles
 of consumption levels.
 We cannot select items that the only richer section of society indulges
 in and claim that people spending on these selected items indicate higher
 status.
 Such a claim is only a restatement of the high permanent income and says
 nothing more substantial than that the richer population sections signal
 higher status.
 It would be a fallacy to associate visible consumption with household character
istics by only associating household characteristics with permanent income.
 The interpretation status in terms of the asset ownership and the barriers
 in society that exist to acquiring these assets - avoids such circular
 notions of status or conspicuous consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\paragraph_spacing single

\size normal
A brief review of the demand theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\paragraph_spacing single

\size normal
Linear Budget Constraint - General restrictions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The linear-budget in the demand theory poses some constraints on the demand
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $q(x,p)$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is the quantity demanded, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the total expenditure and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the vector of prices).
 The key budget constraints are the homogeneity constraint (
\begin_inset Formula $q(\theta x,\theta p)=\theta q(x,p)$
\end_inset

) and the adding-up constraint (
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma p_{k}q_{k}=x)$
\end_inset

.
 The adding-up constraint is often written as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma p_{k}\frac{\partial q_{k}}{\partial x}=1;\ \Sigma p_{k}\frac{\partial g_{k}}{\partial p_{i}}=-q_{i}$
\end_inset

 (for a good 
\begin_inset Formula $i\epsilon[1,n]$
\end_inset

) while the homogeneity restriction as: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma_{k}\frac{p_{k}}{q_{i}}\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial p_{k}}-x\frac{\partial q_{i}}{\partial x}=0$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
These theoretical constraints aren't automatically true for empirical data.
 Instead, their validity needs to be tested.
 For example, in the Working-Leser model - which provides a simple demand
 function (as well as the corresponding Engel curve) with the budget share
 dependent on total expenditure alone ( 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=\beta\cdot log\ x_{i}+\alpha$
\end_inset

 where total expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum p_{i}q_{i}$
\end_inset

, budget share
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=p_{i}q_{i}/x$
\end_inset

 and
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta$
\end_inset

 are regression coefficients) - one needs to make sure that the adding-up
 and homogeneity restrictions apply on the data (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\alpha_{i}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma\beta_{i}=0$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that no commodity specific information is used in the semi-logarithmic
 equation of the Working-Leser model.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
The Engel curves - such as one provided by the Working Leser model - were
 popularised by Houthakker to obtain income and expenditure elasticities
 in a cross-sectional analysis of consumption data 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

.
 One reason why Engel curves have been so popular is their suitability to
 the idea of equivalence scales (i.e.
 how different households achieve a same level of living standard).
 Even though Houthakker's fitting of various Engel curve functions may now
 appear 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

unashamedly pragmatic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 [sic] 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonHandbook"

\end_inset

, it did assist with the an intuitive understanding of the household consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\paragraph_spacing single
A similar intuition employed by Prais-Houthakker - was that of observed
 price differences in commodities consumed.
 Obtained simply by dividing expense with the quantity, Prais-Houthakker
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HouthakkerFamilySurvey"

\end_inset

) calculated the variations in prices amidst different demographics to understan
